<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-135-846  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 135 846.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  March 29 1989 v138 n47,824 pC7(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Improving a computer network's efficiency. (Business Technology)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Markoff, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>As computer networks become more complex, a need evolves todevelop systems that use a network's computational resourcesefficiently.andP;  Researchers at Xerox Corp's Palo Alto ResearchCenter are working on a project that accomplishes efficientallocation of resources by running an 'auction,' in which a user'scomputer bids for time on other computers.andP;  Bids can beprioritized, so that quick access to a particular machine ispossible.andP;  Xerox's research project, called Spawn, requires nocentralized controlling computer.andP;  Spawn has two research goals:to show how to harness idle time in a computer network, and toprovide a way to study complex systems.andP;  Spawn is necessary, sayresearchers, because centralized controller computers areineffective in large networks.andP;  Information, distributedthroughout many computers, changes too rapidly for a centralizedcomputer to monitor.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Xerox Corp. Palo Alto Reserach Center (research).andO;Topic:     NetworksDistributed ProcessingEfficiencyScientific ResearchTheory of ComputationCentralizationDecentralization.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Using an auction to manage a network. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>